{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Guam}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guam\n| map1            = \n| places          = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Guam]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = March 15, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=15|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 82<ref name=\"Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center\">{{cite web |last1=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |title=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center Map |url=https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/ |website=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center |publisher=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 7<ref name=\"The Daily Guam Post: 7 people 'fully recovered' from COVID-19, however governor warns the 'worst is yet to come'\">{{cite web |last1=Daily Post Staff |title=7 people 'fully recovered' from COVID-19, however governor warns the 'worst is yet to come' |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/people-fully-recovered-from-covid--however-governor-warns-the/article_031bbd80-70ab-11ea-b3b2-b7b12050475a.html  |publisher=The Daily Guam Post |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n| deaths          = 3<ref name=\"Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center\">{{cite web |last1=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |title=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center Map |url=https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/ |website=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine Coronavirus Resource Center |publisher=Johns Hopkins University & Medicine |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [http://dphss.guam.gov/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov/ Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]\n}}\nThe [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the United States territory of [[Guam]] on March 15, 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\nOn March 15, 2020, the first three cases of [[COVID-19]] in the territory were confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Anumita|last=Kaur|url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/news/local/2020/03/15/governor-3-guam-confirmed-positive-covid-19/5053098002/ |title=Governor: 3 on Guam confirmed positive for COVID-19|website=Pacific Daily News |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe territory's first death from the virus, a 68-year-old woman with \"multiple [[co-morbidities]]\", was on March 22, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Guam confirms Pacific's first Covid-19 death |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/412328/coronavirus-guam-confirms-pacific-s-first-covid-19-death |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=RNZ |date=22 March 2020 |language=en-nz}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, 2020, the territory had confirmed 45 positive Covid-19 cases out of 308 total tests.<ref name=\"45 of 308 test positive for COVID-19: The Guam Daily Post\">{{cite web |last1=Delgado |first1=Nick |title='There are tough days ahead': 45 of 308 test positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/there-are-tough-days-ahead/article_de77a7a4-6f20-11ea-867e-ab53e1e2b25b.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |publisher=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2020, the Governor's Press Secretary Krystal Paco-San Agustin confirmed two new cases of the coronavirus. Guam's Public Health Lab had tested 20 samples with the remaining 18 coming back negative.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two more Covid-19 cases in Guam |url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/international/pacific-news/413025/two-more-covid-19-cases-in-guam |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=[[Radio New Zealand]] |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!\n!Daily cases\n!Cumulative cases\n!Daily deaths\n!Cumulative deaths\n|-\n|15 March 2020\n|3\n|3\n|\n|\n|-\n|16 March 2020\n|\n|3\n|\n|\n|-\n|17 March 2020\n|2\n|5\n|\n|\n|-\n|18 March 2020\n|3\n|8\n|\n|\n|-\n|19 March 2020\n|4\n|12\n|\n|\n|-\n|20 March 2020\n|2\n|14\n|\n|\n|-\n|21 March 2020\n|1\n|15\n|\n|\n|-\n|22 March 2020\n|12\n|27\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|23 March 2020\n|2\n|29\n|\n|1\n|-\n|24 March 2020\n|3\n|32\n|\n|1\n|-\n|25 March 2020\n|5\n|37\n|\n|1\n|-\n|26 March 2020\n|8\n|45\n|\n|1\n|-\n|27 March 2020\n|6\n|51\n|\n|1\n|-\n|28 March 2020\n|4\n|55\n|\n|1\n|-\n|29 March 2020\n|1\n|56\n|\n|1\n|-\n|30 March 2020\n|2\n|58\n|\n|1\n|-\n|31 March 2020\n|9\n|69\n|1\n|2\n|-\n|1 April 2020\n|8\n|77\n|1\n|3\n|-\n|2 April 2020\n|5\n|82\n|\n|3\n|}\n\n==Prevention==\n[[File:Guam_National_Guard_-_49694586463.jpg|thumb|[[Guam Army National Guard]]sman at a COVID-19 isolation site]]\nOn March 13, 2020, temperature taking began at [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/weeks-after-covid--outbreaks-guam-airport-starts-fever-scans/video_c593acac-64c0-11ea-a456-7ff8e41c1f02.html |title=Weeks after COVID-19 outbreaks, Guam airport starts fever scans |work=The Guam Daily Post |date=March 13, 2020 |access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGovernor [[Lou Leon Guerrero]] issued an executive order shutting down nonessential businesses and gatherings, effective March 20 at noon. The same day, [[Japan Airlines]] announced flights from [[Narita Airport]] would be suspended until April 24.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaur |first1=Anumita |title=Guam seeks federal relief as shut down goes in effect and closures, cancellations continue |url=https://www.guampdn.com/story/money/2020/03/21/guam-seeks-federal-relief-shut-down-effect-and-closures-continue/2882293001/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Pacific Daily News |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn Thursday, March 26, the [[University of Guam]] announced that all classes were moving to an online or alternate format for the remainder of the spring semester. The University plans to complete the semester on its current schedule.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Daily Post Staff |title=UOG classes going online for semester |url=https://www.postguam.com/news/local/uog-classes-going-online-for-semester/article_ab6c7f7c-6f27-11ea-a365-bb1c1b15e4c4.html |website=The Guam Daily Post |publisher=The Guam Daily Post |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn Saturday, March 28, [[President of the United States|United States President]] [[Donald Trump]] approved a disaster declaration for Guam that orders Federal assistance to supplement territory and local coronavirus recovery efforts.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/president-donald-j-trump-approves-guam-disaster-declaration-3/|title=President Donald J. Trump Approves Guam Disaster Declaration|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The President also signed the national $2 trillion COVID-19 relief bill with approximately $111 million allocated to Guam.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://dphss.guam.gov/2019-novel-coronavirus-2019-n-cov/ Coronavirus information] from [[Guam Department of Public Health and Social Services]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Guam|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in insular areas of the United States|Guam]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Oceania|Guam]]\n[[Category:Health in Guam]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n\n{{Guam-stub}}\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Guam}}\n{{Current disas